{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492650"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:39:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:39:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1121"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1121"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.1,0.74,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1121"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44097"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1121"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1121"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29074"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1412"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42220"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43061"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44097"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a one-week history of episodic epigastric discomfort. She reports that over this period, each episode has lasted around 10 minutes, with the discomfort being relieved by lying down on her sofa. The most recent event occurred this morning when she was weeding in the garden. It lasted around 15 minutes and was accompanied by nausea and tiredness. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her medications include perindopril and metformin. On examination, her pulse rate is 94/min, blood pressure 152/92 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Examination of her chest and abdomen is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum lipase","Upper abdominal ultrasound","ECG","Endoscopy","Serum lactate"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst her symptoms appear to be gastrointestinal in nature, the priority must be to exclude cardiac ischaemia. An \u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E is the essential initial investigation. Her symptoms may well be those of atypical myocardial ischaemia - and such presentations are well recognised in women, diabetics and older patients. In diabetes (particularly for poor control or long standing cases), the related autonomic neuropathy will dampen the typical myocardial ischaemia pain that a patient would experience. Women are more likely to present with symptoms such as nausea, fatigue, weakness and shortness of breath, as well as pain or discomfort in unconventional locations for cardiac ischaemia. Given that her symptoms have been transient and episodic, as well as relieved by rest, one should be suspicious of cardiac ischaemia. ECG changes that are suggestive of cardiac ischaemia include ST segment depression and T wave inversion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum lipase\u003C/strong\u003E is an investigation to order if pancreatitis is on the list of differentials. Whilst pancreatitis is associated with epigastric pain (often radiating through to the back), patients will typically present with more severe symptoms that the patient in this case. Symptoms are also progressive and constant, rather than intermittent. As such, serum lipase is an incorrect answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in cases like this one to further investigate biliary and hepatic disease as a cause of symptoms, as well as abdominal aortic aneurysms. Having said that, it is more important to exclude cardiac disease before moving onto alternate pathways of investigation, so an abdominal ultrasound is not the most appropriate initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate in the investigation of peptic ulcer disease and gastritis. Endoscopy is highly sensitive for the diagnosis of gastric and duodenal ulcers and also allows for biopsies and \u003Cem\u003EH.pylori \u003C/em\u003Etesting to be performed. Once again, endoscopy may be indicated in the setting of ongoing symptoms, but only once cardiac disease has been excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum lactate\u003C/strong\u003E becomes elevated in mesenteric ischaemia, a condition that can cause episodic abdominal pain. Patients will often display risk factors for vascular disease and will typically report severe abdominal pain that occurs in association with eating. Classically, the symptoms are said to be out of proportion to examination findings, with abdominal exam often being fairly unremarkable in this cohort of patients. Mesenteric ischaemia can be a difficult condition to diagnose and investigations such as serum lactate should only be performed once other, more common conditions, have been excluded.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A potential myocardial cause for epigastric symptoms must always be considered in older patients."],"references":["Brewer LC, Svatikova A, Mulvagh SL. The challenges of prevention, diagnosis and treatment of ischemic heart disease in women. Cardiovascular Drugs and Therapy. 2015;29(4):355\u201368. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26210899/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1121"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29074"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-06T20:57:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-06T20:57:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1121"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44097"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","